{"data":[{"type":"questionAttempts","id":"17523077","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionAttempts/17523077"},"attributes":{"position":0,"marks":1,"score":0,"answeredAt":"2025-09-29T14:52:07+09:30","options":[1],"response":null,"finalizedAt":"2025-09-29T14:52:07+09:30"},"relationships":{"user":{"data":{"type":"users","id":"50098"}},"questionSession":{"data":null},"session":{"data":null},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"13871"}},"bookmark":{"data":null}}}],"included":[{"type":"questions","id":"13871","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questions/13871"},"attributes":{"optionProportions":[0.31,0.49,0.01,0.03,0.17]},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"6488"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"52777"}}}},{"type":"items","id":"6488","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/items/6488"},"attributes":{"contentType":"question"},"relationships":{"content":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"13871"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"38158"}},"tags":{"data":[{"type":"tags","id":"3"},{"type":"tags","id":"64"},{"type":"tags","id":"72"},{"type":"tags","id":"76"},{"type":"tags","id":"1063"},{"type":"tags","id":"2434"}]},"contributions":{"data":[{"type":"contributions","id":"12879"},{"type":"contributions","id":"14033"},{"type":"contributions","id":"14727"}]}},"meta":{"canRevise":false,"canManage":false,"canDelete":false}},{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"52777","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionRevisions/52777"},"attributes":{"stem":"\u003Cp\u003EA 25-year-old woman presents to the General Practice clinic with a painful rash on her lower limbs that developed over the past few days. She started taking an oral contraceptive pill three weeks ago but has no other significant medical history. She does not take any other regular medications. She does not smoke but does drink two standards of alcohol a day.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EOn examination, she appears in pain but otherwise well with vital signs within normal limits. The rash consists of tender, erythematous nodules on her shins (Image). There is no ulceration of the nodules.\u003C/p\u003E","stemQuestion":"Which one of the following is the most likely diagnosis?","responseType":"sba","marks":1,"options":["Panniculitis","Cutaneous small vessel vasculitis","Scabies","Cellulitis","Toxic epidermal necrolysis"],"correctOptions":[0],"correctResponses":null,"explanation":"\u003Cp\u003EThe clinical presentation described is most consistent with \u003Cstrong\u003Epanniculitis\u003C/strong\u003E, specifically erythema nodosum, which is the most common form of panniculitis. The patient presents with tender, erythematous nodules on the shins, which are characteristic of this condition. Erythema nodosum is often idiopathic but can be associated with various conditions, including infections, medications (such as oral contraceptives), and inflammatory bowel disease. In this case, the recent initiation of oral contraceptive pills is a likely trigger. Management depends on the type and cause of panniculitis, but generally involves treating the underlying cause (which may include discontinuing the oral contraceptive) and providing symptomatic relief with NSAIDs or other anti-inflammatory medications. The lesions typically resolve spontaneously over several weeks.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EScabies\u003C/strong\u003E typically presents with intense itching and a rash consisting of small, red, raised bumps, often in a linear pattern. It commonly affects the hands, wrists, and other areas where skin touches skin. The distribution and appearance of the rash in this case do not match scabies.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003ECutaneous small vessel vasculitis\u003C/strong\u003E can present with palpable purpura, usually on the lower extremities. While it can be associated with systemic diseases, the description of tender nodules is more consistent with panniculitis than vasculitis.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003ECellulitis\u003C/strong\u003E is a bacterial skin infection that typically presents as a warm, erythematous, and tender area of skin. It usually affects one area rather than multiple sites on both legs as described in this case.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EToxic epidermal necrolysis\u003C/strong\u003E is a severe, life-threatening skin reaction usually caused by medications. It presents with widespread erythema, blistering, and sloughing of the skin, often accompanied by severe systemic symptoms. This presentation does not match the description in the case.\u003C/p\u003E","optionExplanations":["","","","",""],"learningPoints":["Panniculitis is inflammation of subcutaneous fat that presents as painful, erythematous nodules or plaques, typically on the lower legs.","Erythema nodosum, a common form of panniculitis, can be associated with medications, systemic disease and infections"],"references":["P\u00e9rez-Garza DM, Chavez-Alvarez S, Ocampo-Candiani J, Gomez-Flores M. Erythema Nodosum: A Practical Approach and Diagnostic Algorithm. Am J Clin Dermatol. 2021;22(3):367-378. Available at: https://pubmed.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/33683567/"]},"relationships":{"itemRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"38158"}},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"13871"}},"stemMedia":{"data":[{"type":"media","id":"20813"}]},"explanationMedia":{"data":[]}}},{"type":"media","id":"20813","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/media/20813"},"attributes":{"mimeType":"image/jpeg","url":"https://app.emedici.com/storage/media/TBy9LEc7szwzFIdHQk7WR74FT2GEkz.jpg","thumbUrl":"https://app.emedici.com/storage/media/TBy9LEc7szwzFIdHQk7WR74FT2GEkz.jpg","isProcessed":true,"width":1500,"height":1125}},{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"38158","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/itemRevisions/38158"},"attributes":{"createdAt":"2024-09-09T19:59:08+09:30","updatedAt":"2024-09-11T12:30:30+09:30"},"relationships":{